      "id": 355444,
      "is_answer_order_important": false,
      "stimulus_html": "",
      "stem_html": "<p>The amino acid methionine is formed by a methylation reaction of homocysteine with <i>N</i>-methyltetrahydrofolate. The stereochemistry of the reaction has been probed by carrying out the transformation using a donor with a “chiral methyl group,” which contains protium (H), deuterium (D), and tritium (T) isotopes of hydrogen. Does the methylation reaction occur with inversion or retention of configuration?</p>\n<img class=\"scaled-down\" src=\"https://exercises.openstax.org/rails/active_storage/blobs/proxy/eyJfcmFpbHMiOnsibWVzc2FnZSI6IkJBaHBBdndUIiwiZXhwIjpudWxsLCJwdXIiOiJibG9iX2lkIn19--717bef4e53ade447f70d8de10eb0bd0270a54445/OChem_11_EC_047.jpg\" alt=\"The reaction of homocysteine in the presence of methionine synthase forms methionine, N-methyltetrahydrofolate, and Tetrahydrofolate.\">",
